1

00:00:02,149  -->  00:00:04,230
In the last video,

2

00:00:04,230  -->  00:00:06,890
we saw that a p-value is the probability of obtaining

3

00:00:06,889  -->  00:00:10,709
our data or more extreme values from the null hypothesis.

4

00:00:10,710  -->  00:00:15,755
So how does this connect to making decisions and the types of errors that we can make?

5

00:00:15,755  -->  00:00:18,185
If the p-value is really small,

6

00:00:18,184  -->  00:00:22,474
this suggests it's less likely to observe our statistic from the null.

7

00:00:22,475  -->  00:00:25,505
And it's more likely that it came from the alternative.

8

00:00:25,504  -->  00:00:27,980
But how small does the p-value need to be

9

00:00:27,980  -->  00:00:31,080
before we no longer stay with the null hypothesis?

10

00:00:31,079  -->  00:00:36,045
Well, I guess that depends on how willing you are to make certain types of errors.

11

00:00:36,045  -->  00:00:39,065
If you are willing to commit five percent of errors,

12

00:00:39,064  -->  00:00:41,585
where you choose the alternative incorrectly,

13

00:00:41,585  -->  00:00:43,789
then your p-value needs to be smaller than

14

00:00:43,789  -->  00:00:47,085
this threshold in order to choose the alternative.

15

00:00:47,085  -->  00:00:50,719
However, if your probability of getting the data from the null is, say,

16

00:00:50,719  -->  00:00:52,265
an eight percent chance,

17

00:00:52,265  -->  00:00:54,710
this is enough of a chance that you would stay with

18

00:00:54,710  -->  00:00:57,905
the null under a five percent type one error threshold.

19

00:00:57,905  -->  00:01:02,183
The fast rule is that if our p-value is less than a type one error rate,

20

00:01:02,183  -->  00:01:04,524
then professionals say we reject the null.

21

00:01:04,525  -->  00:01:07,660
That is, we choose the alternative hypothesis.

22

00:01:07,659  -->  00:01:10,474
If the p-value is greater than our type one error rate,

23

00:01:10,474  -->  00:01:12,459
then we fail to reject the null.

24

00:01:12,459  -->  00:01:15,564
That is, we stay with the null hypothesis as our decision.

25

00:01:15,564  -->  00:01:17,259
What's actually true?

26

00:01:17,260  -->  00:01:19,115
We can't really be sure in practice,

27

00:01:19,114  -->  00:01:22,039
but we now have a database way to make our decisions.
